{"/service/ndnp/mthi/batch_mthi_ivy_ver01/data/sn83004278/00340581982/1958042401/0241.xml":{"full_text":"2 THE STOWET HERALD\nThursday. April 24. 1958\nVk. SuLty JJ.ratd\nC. K. HCKLI\nomoAL NxwapAFB or\nRICHLAND COUNTY, MONTANA\nNAH ON At\nOJ VOUAI\nI\nkfi\nASS\n\u25a0\u2022MH 4M\n\u00ab\u00bblocution\nEntered at the Postoffice at Sidney,\nMontana, as Second Class Matter March\n13. 1908, under the Act of Mach 3. i\u00ab78. j\ni\n\nI\n\nPublished every Thursday at Sidney\nRichland County. Montana.\nSUBSCRIPTION RATES\nRictiland-McKenne Counties. $3.00\nyear; $3 5o a year in Montana: $400 a\nyear outside Montana Single copies 18c.\nForeign Countries $5.50.\nEDITORIALLY\nNEW SAFETY DEVICE\nThe Ford Motor Company has\ndeveloped an electronic device\nwhich will flash a warning to\nthe driver following too closely\nbehind a car. It is an effort to\nprevent rear-end collisions on\nthe part of the automobile com\npany, and is a promising one.\nA survey in the Detroit area\nrevealed recently that of the\nmany accidents occurring on the\nDetroit Expressway, some 57.5%\nof the accidents in 1956 were\nrear-end collisions.\nThe new safety device picks\nup the headlight illumination of\nthe car behind and computes the\ndistance. If the car approaches\ntoo close, the device trips a switch\nthat flashes the red brake signal,\nwarning the following driver to\ndrop back.\nThis is a safety device much\nneeded. It is also needed in day\nlight hours. One might be work\ned out for both day and night\noperation, using radar as the\nsource of warning\nnot too expensive.\nThe night time device is not\nif this is\nwant a handier\nkitchen\nif.\n\nA.\n\nr\nf\n\nx\nm\n\n\n\nYou'll be delighted with the\nconvenience of o kitchen tele\nphone. Costs only pennies a\nday. Easy to order. Just coil\nour business office.\nmodern homes have\nhandy phones\u2014in c\nMountain States Telephono\n\"Now I\npay all\nmy bills\nin one\nplace!\"\nj\na\nVA\nV\n\nw\ni\nto be, around the\n\"What a messenger boy I used\nfirst of the month-hiking all over town with\ncash. No more. In half an hour I can write checks\nto pay all my bills\u2014 drop 'em in the comer mail\nbox\u2014and that's that!\nN\nWHY NOT OPB4 YOUK\nSTH*-SAVING CHECKING\nACCOUNT WITH US SOON?\n^RICHLAND NATIONA.\nOF SIDNEY\n,r 7kl.\nMEM\u00dftKTEDEKAL DEPOSIT INS\u00fcK\u00c2NC\u00cf\u00d4\u00d4R\u00ee\u00d4P\u00c2^\u00d4n\nI\ngreatly different from a light\ndimmer which has been used on\nGeneral Motors cars, and other\ncars, for some years, in principle.\nThe idea at putting a warning\ndevice on the rear of a car is\nan excellent one, however, and\nit is thought this will help cut\ndown the number of rear-end\ncollisions.\nWhen the companies can pro\nduce a warning light on the\nrear which will cut on auto\nmatically both day and night, on\nthe open highways, our safety\nrecord will probably be further\nimproved,\ncould shoot tobacco juice on the\napproaching car, its effectiveness\nwould be greatly enhanced.\nAnd, if the device\nTHE ECONOMIC FUTURE\nA group of leading business\nexecutives has launched a cam\npaign to counteract what is called\n\"recession fever.\" The business\nmen believe that recession fever\ncan grip those who have not been\nhurt financially and that fear of\na recession can stop their pur\nchases and make the recession\nmuch worse than it should be.\nThe group recalls that in 1954\nwhen a small recession was ex\nperienced, a similar effort was\nmade by them and was credited\nwith having a beneficial effect\non the economy. In brief, the\nprogram of the businessmen is\nto conduct an advertising drive,\nin an effort to convince Ameri\ncans that the economy is basic\nally sound, and that the future\nof this country is bright.\nThere is no question but that\nthe future of our country, eco\nnomically, is bright. We have an\nexpanding population, an increas\ning number of families each year,\nand more jobs are averaged out\nover the long run.\nthere is no doubt that the pres\nent economy is suffering a re\ncession, and there is no reason\nfor anyone to hide the fact.\nThe recession should not in\nduce those who are not hurt by\nit to curtail buying. On this\ncount, the group of advertisers\nis performing a public service by\nurging people to continue their\nnormal buying habits, or take\nadvantage of bargains, and not be\nfrightened into stapling their wal\nlets closed.\nHowever\nWe applaud the effort of the\nbusinessmen, both those connect\ned with national concerns, and\nthose locally, who are seeking to\nstimulate buying and lessen the\neffects of the recession. There is\nno necessity\ning any worse than it is, and a\npsychological factor is certainly\ninvolved in today's reduced buy\ning.\nEMPLOYER MUST\nREPORT S. S. TAXES\nON BABYSITTERS\nDo you employ a maid, a cook,\na laundress, baby sitter, or others\nto help with your household\nchores? If you do, and you pay\nsuch a domestic employee $50 or\nmore cash wages in a calendar\nquarter of the year, you are re\nminded by Glenn A. Gardner, dis\ntrict manager of the Billings so\ncial security office, that you must\nreport to the Director of Internal\nRevenue the social security taxes\non the cash wages paid this em\nployee.\nGardner said that a convenient\nenvelope type of tax return (Form\n942) which takes just a moment\nor two to complete, may be\nobtained by household employers\nfrom the district director of In\nternal Revenue. Once registered\nwith the District Director of In\nternal Revenue, the household\nemployer will receive the simpli\nfied tax return automatically each\nquarter. The total tax to be re\nmitted is 4%% of the cash wages\npaid to the domestic worker dur\ning the calendar quarter; the em\nployer may deduct one-half of\nthis or 2*4% from the employee's\npay. Only the first $4200 of year\nly cash is taxable.\nAdditional information\nand benefits payable may be ob\ntained by contacting Chester Bu\nchanan, representative of\nBillings social security office when\nhe is in Sidney.\nabout\nthe\nProsperous\nValley\nBy Mrs. An tea\u00ab Card*\nMrs. Harry Hagen accompan\nied Mrs. Klasna to Glendive Mon\nday.\nMr. and Mrs. Lloyd Sheehan\nand Rickie were callers in Lam\nbert Tuesday and also attended\nthe Eddie Bell sale. Mr. and Mrs.\nJames Vaira and David attended\nthe Bell sale also.\nMrs. Antone Carda and Jim\ncalled at the Kenneth Klasna\nhome Tuesday morning,\nevening Mr. and Mrs. Second\u00a9\nPistocco visited the Antone Car\nda's.\nSusan Carda stayed overnight\nwith Charlene Vaira Tuesday,\nand Connie Sheehan spent the\nnight with Sharon Carda.\nMrs. Kenneth Klasna, Edmund\nand Linda visited Mrs. Albert\nCarda Tuesday afternoon at the\nGeorge Carda home.\nEdmund and Linda Klasna vis\nited at the Antone Carda home\nWednesday while their mother\nwent to Glendive where she is\ntaking treatments.\nMr. and Mrs. George Carda\nand Chuck and Mrs. John Carda\narrived home about 2:00 Wednes\nday morning. The George Cardas\nbought a place near Kalispell but\nrented it for this year while\nthey attend to matters of a sale,\netc., here. They are \"Old Tim\ners of this community and we\nregret to see them leave us, but\nhope they will be happy at their\nnew location.\nMr. and Mrs. Guido Vaira and\nVickie called at the James Vaira\nhome Thursday.\nThat\nCallers at the George Carda\nhome Thursday were Mr. and\nMrs. Joseph Klasna and Timmie,\nMrs. Mary Pistocco, and Mrs.\nAntone Carda and children.\nMr. and Mrs. Lloyd Sheehan\nand family motored to Sidney\nafter school Thursday.\nVisitors of the Antone Cardas\nThursday evening were Mr. and\nMrs. George Carda and Chuck.\nMr. and Mrs. Albert Lowe and\nMrs. Hull were shoppers in Glen\ndive Friday.\nJim Brenner was a caller at\nthe James Vaira home Friday\nmorning.\nMr. and Mrs. Lloyd Sheehan\nand family, and Sharon and Su\nsan Carda were callers in Lam\nbert after school Friday.\nMr. and Mrs. Bert Christian\nson motored to Sidney Friday af\nter school.\nMrs. Jean Hepler called at the\nKenneth Klasna home Saturday.\nMrs. John Carda took Mrs. Al\nbert Carda back to Sidney Wed\nnesday as she had been staying\nat the George Carda home while\nthey were gone.\nMrs. Emma Fink called at the\nJames Vaira home Thursday on\nher way to Sidney.\nMr. and Mrs. Antone Carda\nand family were Saturday eve\nning visitors of the Lloyd Shee\nhan's.\nKenneth Klasna was a business\ncaller in Fairview and Sidney\nSaturday.\nSunday dinner guests at the\nAntone Carda home were Mr.\nand Mrs. Frank Carda and boys,\nAnton Carda, Sr. and Bob.\nPower City\nBy Mrs. Raben Hamburg\nWelcome to the community! Mr.\nand Mrs. Robert Vester and fam\nily who moved on the Dave Ker\nbel farm March 22. They have\nthree children attending the Gos\nsett school, Janet, Murray and\nDarlene. Verla is attending Sid\nney high school; they have two\npre-school children, ages 4 and\n5, and four older sons 3 of\nwhom are living in Regina, Sask.,\nand one is in the Canadian Air\nForce at Winnipeg, Man. Bob\nJr. returned to Canada Wednes\nday after spending two weeks\nvisiting here.\nMrs. George Scheetz attended\na meeting in Sidney Tuesday\nnight to discuss plans for the\nannual Talent Night sponsored\nby the 4-H club council.\nWednesday\ndinner\nevening\nguests at the Howard Blodgett\nhome were Mr. and Mrs. Ray\nBlomquist of Sidney.\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Scheetz\nmotored to Glendive Sunday to\nvisit John Kaufman. Mrs. Kauf\nman passed away at the end of\nlast week. The Kaufmans were\nformerly of Fairview.\nSunday dinner guests of Mr.\nand Mrs. Marvin Rau were Mr.\nand Mrs. Wilmer Lorenz and\nfamily.\nSunday afternoon visitors at\nthe Robert Vester home were\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Nollmeyer\nand family of Savage, and Mr.\nand Mrs. Ruben Hamburg and\nfamily.\nMr. and Mrs. Kent Anderson\nand girls spent Thursday evening\nat the Russell Mercer home.\nJim Mercer attended a massed\nchorus practice at Glendive Fri\nday and the music festival Sat\nurday.\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Bather\nand family were Sunday dinner\nguests of Mr. and Mrs. Richard\nSchannon in Fairview, the oc\ncasion being Mr. and Mrs. Schon\nnoo's birthdays.\nLarry Mindt caught an 18 lb.\nsturgeon in the river Saturday.\nThe fish was 52 inches long and\nwas very good eating.\nJoe Kelly and Clarence Sather\ncalled at the Henry Sather home\nSunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Russell Mercer\nand family visited Mr. and Mrs.\nAlbert Petersen on Friday eve\nning. Saturday evening Mrs. Mer\ncer and daughters called at the\nBlodgett and R. Hamburg's.\nVisiting at the Henry Bux\nbaum home last week Monday\nevening were Mr. and Mrs. John\nSchmidt Jr., Mr. and Mrs. Jake\nMarker, Mr. and Mrs. Henry\nScheetz and also Mrs. Scheetz's\nparents, Mr. and Mrs. August\nGable of Hardin, Montana.\nThe Kallevig brothers have\nbuilt a new road from the high\nway to their new home located\nbetween the Schmidt and Henry\nHamburg homes near the new\npower plant.\nNewlon school will be guests\nof the Rau school Friday after\nnoon, April 25 at the annual ball\ngame. Everyone invited.\nMr. and Mrs. Philip Scheetz\nand son Kenneth spent Sunday\nafternoon visiting at the Conrad\nStrashiem home. Other visitors\nwere Mr. and Mrs. Rhineholt\nKling and family of Miles City.\nThursday afternoon, April 24\nat 2 o'clock was the annual spel\nling bee for Rau school students,\nparents and friends being invited.\nThis was a prelude to the final\nspelling contest to be held at\nthe Sidney high school auditorium\nSaturday, April 26, 9 a. m. to\n4 p. m.\nA school board meeting was\nheld at the Russell Mercer home\nSaturday evening, April 19. Plans\nwere discussed about consolidat\ning the three schools of this area,\nnothing final being decided.\nMr. and Mrs. Henry Thompson\nvisited at the Lewis Albert home\nSunday.\nMr. and Mrs. Mutt Adams and\nfamily visited Sunday evening\nat the Russell Mercer home.\nMr. and Mrs. Ray Blodgett\nvisited at the Howard Blodgett\nhome Sunday evening.\nMr. and Mrs. Ed Uhrich and\nfamily were Sunday\nguests at the Henry Rau home.\ndinner\nCharley Creek\nBy Ruffatto School\nMr. and Mrs. George Fisher\nand boys visited at the Alvin\nFisher home Monday evening.\nMrs. Alvin Fisher went to Sid\nney Monday to help her mother,\nMrs. Hazil Houglum clean house.\nMr. and Mrs. Raymond Ruf\nfatto were callers in Sidney on\nWednesday.\nMr. and Mrs. Howard Smith\nwere callers in Culbertson Tues\nday.\nMrs. George Fisher was col^\nlecting for the cancer fund Mon\nday. Her son Jerry visited at\nthe Quinto Ruffatto home while\nshe called at the other homes.\nShe was a luncheon guest at\nthe Wm. Fisher home.\nMrs. Harry Foss and children\nand Mrs. Alvin Fisher were visi\nKIRBY CO. of Sidney\nKIRBY VACUUM\nSolo* and Service\nFREE Demonstration\nBOB WAGNER\nDistrict Representative\nPhone 303-J\n3*2 N. Central\ny\nm\nI\n\u00cf;\nMod\u00ab I 3104 St\u00abp$Ido, abov\u00ab, tKo\nlow\u00abtt pric\u00abd popular pickup!\n\ni\nI\n\nyy.\nW--.\nF\nN\u00abw high-copoclfy Floofsido\nbody I\u00bb deeper oi*d wider!\nSpace for bigger cargoes... and a special way of saving!\nFirst in buyer preference since 1937\nAH Task-Force pickups offer the 6-cylinder\nengine best known for economy. All offer\nload features like a graintight tailgate and\nsteel skid strips in the hardwood floor.\nYour Chevrolet dealer has 'em\u2014the year's\nfinest lineup, including America's lowest\npriced popular pickup.\nChevy's high-capacity pickup line, In\ncluding the new Fleetside, has a quick\nanswer to anybody's overhead problem.\nYou can tell the new Fleetside is wider\nfull 6 feet wide-deeper too; built to\nyou trips with its extra-big capacity.\nTHE BIG WHEEL IN TRUCKS\n\u2022a ve\nSee your local authorized Chevrolet dealer\nGem City Motor Company\n203 S. Central\nSidney, Montana\ntors at the Wm. Fisher home last\nThursday.\nMr. and Mrs. Pete P. Ruffatto\nvisited at the Harry Foss home\nSunday afternoon.\nMr. and Mrs. Junior Miller\nand Tommy and Mr. and Mrs.\nGeorge Fisher and two boys vis\nited at the Wm. Fisher's Thurs\nday evening.\nMr, and Mrs. Harold Fink and\nchildren of Lambert were Sunday\ndinner and supper guests at the\nA1 Schmitz home.\nFather Heretick was a Sunday\nsupper guest at the Anton Schmitz\nhome.\nMr. and Mrs. Pete P. Ruffatto\nwent to Culbertson Friday for\nthe high school students. Mrs.\nLetty Wesin accompanied them\nand from there she took the bus\nto Sidney where she was a week\nend guest at the Andrew Peter\nsen home. Sunday night she was\nan overnight guest at the Paul\nPatch home. She came home\nMonday morning with Mr. Patch,\nwho is working at the Raymond\nfatto and children Frank and\nand Quinto Ruffatto's.\nThe Wm. and Alvin Fisher\nfamilies went to Sidney Satur\nday to visit with their father,\nBailey Fisher, who left Sunday\nmorning for Billings to enter a\nhospital for a checkup.\nMr. and Mrs. Raymond Ruf\nThelma, Leroy and Gloria Fish\ner and Julia Ruffatto attended\nthe dance at the Andes hall Sat\nurday night.\nM\u00abna News\nBy Mona School\nMrs. Harold Martin and Mrs.\nFlorence Spencer shopped in\nFairview and Sidney Tuesday.\nThey had dinner with the Bert\nDanielsons.\nMrs. Calvin Steppler and Dean\nvisited Mrs. Victor Heiland and\nDon Monday morning.\nMr. and Mrs. Lloyd Parsons\nand girls were in Culbertson\nWednesday.\nMrs. Calvin Steppler and Dean\ncalled on Mrs. Baker Finnicum\nTuesday afternoon.\nThe Homemakers club met at\nthe Mona hall Thursday with\nthe following members present;\nMrs. Harold Martin, Mrs. Flor\nence Spencer, Mrs. Calvin Step\npier, Mrs. Henry Peterson, Mrs.\nBaker Finnicum and children,\nMrs. Ellen Edeburn, Mrs. George\nFisher, Mrs. Lloyd Parsons. Vis\nitors were Mrs. Junior Foss and\nJerry, Mrs. Kenneth Foss and\n8lGVVf6\nthe\nAkidfcckat\nof\nCanned Foods\nBIGWIG\nMrs. Harry Sherman. Mrs. Vic\ntor Heiland was hostess and serv\ned a delicious lunch.\nLate Thursday afternoon Mrs.\nH. Martin and Duane and Mrs.\nHaste and Dorlin went crocus\npicking. The Hastes were supper\nguests of the Martins and spent\nan enjoyable evening there.\nCalvin Steppler took Sharon\nSteppler to the Bidegaray home\nFriday after school, where she\nspent the week end.\nMr. and Mrs. Bert Bidegaray\nwere in Sidney Thursday, where\nMrs. Bidegaray had two teeth\nextracted.\nMr. and Mrs. Reitar Coffman\nand Connie were in Sidney Fri\nday.\nMr. and Mrs. Edgar Kellar an\nnounced Sunday that they are\ngrandparents again. A baby boy\nwas born Friday to Mr. and\nMrs. Leland Keller of Glasgow.\nHe has been named Larry Allan.\nThe Kellers have one other son.\nJean and Bob Barber and O.\nH. Parsons came out from Sid\nney Saturday,\nMr. and Mrs. Calvin Steppler\nand boys visited with the Harold\nMartins Friday evening.\nMrs. Victor Heiland, Lloyd Par\nsons, Jr. Miller and Harold Mar\ntin met at the school house Sat\nurday for a school meeting. Mr.\nMiller is the new trustee.\nBaker Finhicum called at the\nC. Steppler home Saturday.\nJean Bidegaray called at the\nMartins Sunday afternoon to give\nDuane a couple of bum lambs.\nJoAnn, Kathleen, Donnie and\nWhat a\nBig Job\nThey Gave MEI\n44\nff\n\"Perhaps my bark will scare burglars away, or\nsound the alarm in case of fire, but the family\nought to know that the safest place to keep their\nvaluables is in a safe deposit box at the bank!\nRent one from us at low cost\nSidney National Bank\nSJBNEY, MONTANA\nMEMBER FEDERAL DEPOSIT INSURANCE CORPORATION\nBobby Steppler called at the Cal\nSteppler home Sunday morning.\nMr. and Mrs. Paul Amestoy\nand family visited Mr. and Mrs.\nBert Bldegaray and Jean B. Son\nday evening last week.\nI\nRENT\nt\n1\nM I\u00dcY\nFORMAL\ni\nWEAR\n\nA\nfor\n\nWedding\u00bb\nDonees\nAll\ns\nf/C'}\nS\nFormal\nOccasions\nWhite\nCoots\nTuxedo\nPants\nTuxedoes\ns\n1\ns\n\nf MINS and \u00bbOYS STORK\n2910 Second Avenue North\nBOXINGS. MONTANA\nh\ns\nI","height":"22017","width":"16767"}}
